00:26:13,031 --> 00:26:21,129
Rym: Or you buy a PC that is "Xbox certified," meaning it has the, you know, whatever level of performance, and Xbox game will just work on either one.

465
00:26:21,414 --> 00:26:21,690
Scott: Maybe.

466
00:26:22,351 --> 00:26:26,228
Rym: And I think Nintendo is going to hold on to their proprietary bullshit until the bitter end.

467
00:26:26,591 --> 00:26:33,249
Rym: But if Nintendo were smart, they would do what Sega did and turn it into an IP company primarily, and the only hardware I would sell would be portable hardware.

468
00:26:34,390 --> 00:26:39,530
Rym: And officially licensed controllers in the shape of NES, SNES, N64, GameCube controllers.

469
00:26:39,830 --> 00:26:40,450
Scott: That's another thing.

470
00:26:40,550 --> 00:26:53,910
Rym: If Nintendo just made, like, PC-compatible USB controllers and stuff like that-- Nintendo has probably-- They're one of the few companies that has such a wealth of intellectual property that it is unnerving and ludicrous.

471
00:26:54,891 --> 00:26:56,110
Scott: And yet they don't capitalize on it.

472
00:26:57,474 --> 00:27:00,629
Scott: They should take a lesson from the ponies, and they should let Mario go free.

473
00:27:07,160 --> 00:27:10,940
Rym: But anyway, things of the day, now that we're past the lounge.

474
00:27:11,440 --> 00:27:11,565
Scott: Uh-huh.

475
00:27:12,041 --> 00:27:12,334
Rym: Uh-huh.

476
00:27:13,040 --> 00:27:27,220
Rym: So remember a long time ago I made a thing of the day, Garfield minus Garfield, which was basically someone was taking every Garfield comic, erasing Garfield, just leaving John, and that was the comic.

477
00:27:27,320 --> 00:27:35,840
Rym: And it turns out that Garfield without Garfield is not only funnier than Garfield, but it's one of the better comics I've ever read.

478
00:27:36,143 --> 00:27:36,900
Scott: I wouldn't say that.

479
00:27:36,940 --> 00:27:38,140
Rym: There's something great about it.

480
00:27:38,260 --> 00:27:39,703
Rym: It's basically the story-- It gets in.

481
00:27:39,724 --> 00:27:40,740
Scott: It's the same thing over and over again.

482
00:27:40,881 --> 00:27:43,260
Rym: It's a little-- It's not really the same thing over and over.

483
00:27:43,582 --> 00:27:45,060
Rym: I was reading through it again, and it cracks me up.

484
00:27:45,120 --> 00:27:48,100
Rym: It's just basically one man's descent into lonely madness.

485
00:27:48,740 --> 00:27:48,829
Scott: Yeah.

486
00:27:50,352 --> 00:27:56,399
Rym: But-- So this is obviously a borderline fair use, something we were just talking about.

487
00:27:56,880 --> 00:28:00,700
Rym: Well, it was announced at Comic-Con, and this is all legit.

488
00:28:00,801 --> 00:28:06,991
Rym: Jim Davis thinks that Garfield minus Garfield is hilarious, and Ballantine Books and Paws,

489
00:28:07,092 --> 00:28:07,837
Rym: Inc.,

490
00:28:07,957 --> 00:28:17,680
Rym: Random House, everyone got together, and Garfield minus Garfield is being released as a legit book with all the blessings of the people who own the Garfield copyright and Jim Davis.

491
00:28:17,800 --> 00:28:22,260
Scott: Does any of that money go to the guy who came up with Garfield minus Garfield, or does all of it go to Jim Davis?

492
00:28:22,480 --> 00:28:28,276
Rym: It looks like it's going to the people who made Garfield minus Garfield and everybody.

493
00:28:28,900 --> 00:28:29,800
Rym: They're all getting money.

494
00:28:29,921 --> 00:28:32,420
Rym: It's a legit, straight-up just deal that they made.

495
00:28:32,620 --> 00:28:33,040
Scott: So here's the thing.

496
00:28:33,060 --> 00:28:34,493
Scott: This might sound a little extreme, right?

497
00:28:35,360 --> 00:28:42,939
Scott: But actually, I would say I would have no problem with all the money going to the guy who came up with the Garfield minus Garfield, because think of it this way.

498
00:28:43,040 --> 00:28:43,085
Rym: No.

499
00:28:44,021 --> 00:28:48,119
Scott: If you're Andy Warhol and you do Campbell's Soup cans, how much money should go to Campbell's Soup?

500
00:28:49,021 --> 00:28:49,980
Scott: Zero dollars, right?

501
00:28:50,081 --> 00:28:56,520
Scott: You wouldn't have a problem with that, so why would you have a problem-- You know, who here thinks money should go to Campbell's Soup because of Andy Warhol selling a painting?

502
00:28:57,000 --> 00:28:58,738
Rym: Put your hand down, Chef Boyardee.

503
00:29:01,294 --> 00:29:01,420
Scott: Right?

504
00:29:02,584 --> 00:29:07,440
Scott: So, you know, along those lines, that is pretty much what is going on here.

505
00:29:07,520 --> 00:29:12,776
Scott: Well, the other argument you can make is that what the guy-- I'm sure someone out there is saying, "Yeah, the Campbell's Soup should get

506
00:29:12,816 --> 00:29:12,979
Scott: money.".

507
00:29:13,040 --> 00:29:15,960
Rym: Is that what the guy did, right, is removing Garfield from Garfield?

508
00:29:16,601 --> 00:29:21,100
Rym: Because he didn't have the rights to it, and because it was-- You'd have to argue whether or not it was parody.

509
00:29:22,222 --> 00:29:24,239
Rym: So what if someone makes parody of your work?

510
00:29:24,542 --> 00:29:27,279
Rym: that consists of nothing but your work with something removed?

511
00:29:27,702 --> 00:29:33,800
Rym: If you take your own work and remove the same thing, is that your copyright or that person's copyright?

512
00:29:35,920 --> 00:29:37,600
Scott: It's-- What part of it is copyrighted?

513
00:29:37,680 --> 00:29:38,679
Scott: The original copyright.

514
00:29:39,040 --> 00:29:46,200
Scott: You know, the original artwork is-- You know, it's-- Any piece of art has parts, and you can't just get a copyright for the whole thing.

515
00:29:46,380 --> 00:29:49,500
Scott: It's, you know, artwork-- You know, look at movie credits, right?

516
00:29:49,701 --> 00:29:51,259
Rym: That's because different people make those things.

517
00:29:51,540 --> 00:29:56,359
Rym: If I publish a comic that I wrote and drew, it's my copyright for the entire work.

518
00:29:57,422 --> 00:29:58,980
Rym: Not separated between the different bits.

519
00:29:59,140 --> 00:29:59,640
Scott: That is true.

520
00:29:59,820 --> 00:30:05,559
Scott: But now if I remove, say, Spider-Man from Spider-Man, I take a Spider-Man comic, and I erase all the Spider-Mans, right?

521
00:30:06,061 --> 00:30:10,800
Scott: You get credit for all of it except for the removal of the Spider-Mans, which is mine.

522
00:30:11,560 --> 00:30:14,260
Rym: Yeah, so how do we sort out the money situation there?

523
00:30:15,702 --> 00:30:21,400
Scott: I'm not really gonna be making money on it because I don't think you should be able to do anything commercial with a fair use.

524
00:30:21,680 --> 00:30:22,240
Rym: Otherwise, it's not so fair.

525
00:30:22,606 --> 00:30:23,160
Rym: Here's my argument.

526
00:30:23,300 --> 00:30:25,880
Rym: I think you should, but it should be just like music.

527
00:30:26,002 --> 00:30:27,040
Rym: Statutory royalties.

528
00:30:27,760 --> 00:30:28,740
Scott: Statutory royalties, fine.

529
00:30:28,840 --> 00:30:39,940
Rym: Because I think the benefit of anyone being able to use anyone's intellectual property, but if they do it commercially, they're forced to pay, I think that would cause more works to be made than any other alternative.

530
00:30:40,440 --> 00:30:46,040
Scott: Yeah, 'cause imagine if YouTube, instead of you got a takedown notice, you had PayPal $1 to have this video go back up.

531
00:30:46,260 --> 00:30:46,347
Scott: Yeah.

532
00:30:47,221 --> 00:30:51,220
Rym: Actually, that would probably make a lot of people who make music a lot of money.

533
00:30:51,580 --> 00:30:54,120
Rym: Probably more money than they make from album sales.

534
00:30:54,969 --> 00:30:55,119
Rym: Yeah.

535
00:30:55,323 --> 00:30:56,300
Rym: Food for thought, but anyway.

536
00:30:56,540 --> 00:30:59,999
Scott: Or like instead of a dollar, it could be like a tenth of a cent per view.

537
00:31:00,823 --> 00:31:04,399
Rym: Oh, that could get bad really quick though, but then again, that's only for commercial use.

538
00:31:04,862 --> 00:31:05,040
Scott: Exactly.

539
00:31:05,380 --> 00:31:14,359
Scott: If you have ads on the video or something like that, if the video is not making you any money, then it's just in your channel for free with no ads on it, then you don't have to pay anything.

540
00:31:14,880 --> 00:31:18,800
Rym: So anyway, Garfield Minus Garfield, the book is coming out on the 30th anniversary of Garfield.

